Rida Rasheed

12/01/18

<a href="http://www.mhcbusiness.nyc/news/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/gettyimages-880231204.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-733 aligncenter" src="http://www.mhcbusiness.nyc/news/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/gettyimages-880231204-300x169.jpg" alt="" width="488" height="275" /></a>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Since we were children we’ve heard that “slow and steady wins the race”, and in recent years Microsoft has proven this statement to be very true. When naming big tech companies in the market today, many would quickly say Apple or Samsung; Microsoft would maybe be making it to the top five of that list. Surprisingly, this tech company has been doing extremely well and is now worth over $850 billion, a number that is extremely similar to Apple’s worth as well. In fact, these two tech giants have been competing with each other for the title as the world's most valuable company. In the last year alone the stock prices for Microsoft have risen by 30%, and they have tripled since 2014. </span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">This type of rapid growth for such an established company is not extremely common, which leads people to wonder how Microsoft managed to achieve this. This success directly corresponds with Satya Nadella becoming the CEO of Microsoft. One of the best decisions that was made by the administration of the company was to not give into the lure of instant gratification. They took time to learn from their past mistakes and made decisions that would be beneficial for the company in the long run. Microsoft previously had numerous products in many different markets. They cut those products down and have now shifted their focus more towards their cloud service and Office programs such as Word, PowerPoint, adn Excel. </span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Instead of competing with big firms in cutthroat industries, Microsoft decided to step back and aim towards improving the products that were in less demanding industries. Specifically, Microsoft removed itself from the smartphone industry and has allowed Apple, Samsung, and other companies to share that market. I think that one of the best qualities that Microsoft has demonstrated is that the company itself is versatile. They have been open to trying new strategies and learning from their mistakes, a big reason that I believe the company has been able to bounce back with so much success. Many times when companies don’t adapt to a situation they start to sink. Microsoft has successfully been able to the exact opposite, which should make us excited to see what new innovations are to come from this tech giant.</span>

&nbsp;

Source: <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/29/technology/microsoft-apple-worth-how.html">https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/29/technology/microsoft-apple-worth-how.html</a>

